SIMPLE: external
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: External
<hw>Ex*ter"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>externus</ets>, fr. <ets>exter</ets>, <ets>exterus</ets>, on the
outside, outward. See <er>Exterior</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Outward; exterior; relating to the outside, as of a body; being
without; acting from without; -- opposed to <ant>internal</ant>; <as>as,
the <ex>external</ex> form or surface of a body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of all <qex>external</qex> things, . . . ⟦br⟧
She [Fancy] forms imaginations, aery shapes.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Outside of or separate from ourselves;
<fld>(Metaph.)</fld> separate from the perceiving mind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Outwardly perceptible; visible; physical or
corporeal, as distinguished from mental or moral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her virtues graced with <qex>external</qex> gifts.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not intrinsic nor essential; accidental;
accompanying; superficial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>external</qex> circumstances are greatly different.</q>
<rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Foreign; relating to or connected with foreign
nations; <as>as, <ex>external</ex> trade or commerce; the
<ex>external</ex> relations of a state or kingdom.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Away from the mesial plane of the
body; lateral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>External angles</b></col>. <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Angle</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>External</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: External
<hw>Ex*ter"nal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Something external or without;
outward part; that which makes a show, rather than that which is
intrinsic; visible form; -- usually in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Adam was then no less glorious in his <qex>externals</qex></q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God in <qex>externals</qex> could not place content.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>externalisation</ent>⟦br⟧
